[{"sha":"d22deab9f9beb7dfafb2ec332478bd1b53d78d6f","author":{"name":"Charly Molter","email":"0bf65b3a46647433ba986e4a2e1eee2b81710fbd@gmail.com"},"message":"fix(kuma-cp): Sort services by name when selecting them (#2505)

The default sort in k8s is by CreationTimestamp.
In the case of a deployment created in 2 different k8s clusters if
the services were not created in the same order the inbounds would be
generated in a different order which was confusing to the user.

We therefore sort services by names which will always be correct accross zones

Fix #2500

used locally, and added unneeded complexity.

[{"sha":"d90eab6fcea6738e2909ea2e5b7abc119fe6711a","author":{"name":"Tom Hennigan","email":"31b31641eebbee0b3e16a519fc95fcfec3ff2653@google.com"},"message":"Add TF_ENABLED_DEVICE_TYPES env variable to control which devices TF enables.

Many JAX users make heavy use of TensorFlow on CPU for tasks such as data
loading, processing, saved model etc. These users will use JAX to run programs
on GPU/TPU.

GPU users have reported running near the limit of GPU memory, and we have
tracked this down to them unknowingly running some operations on GPU with TF,
and TF allocating a significant chunk of GPU memory on top of JAX's chunk. This
happens particularly often in TF2 (some statements (e.g. `tfds.load(..)`)
eagerly create TF constants placed on the GPU, users struggle to identify this
code as being responsible for using TF on GPU).

It would be convenient if there was an environment variable we could set to
force all usages of TF in a given program to be CPU only. This is similar in
spirit to variables such as CUDA_VISIBLE_DEVICES. It would be easy for training
framework developers to deploy for all of their users (e.g. in the same way we
set some sensible defaults for NCCL to improve performance). Given this CL we
can implement this by setting `TF_ENABLED_DEVICE_TYPES=CPU`.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 389741331

[{"sha":"b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20","author":{"name":"Hkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Add pre-load CPU feature guard check

Compile a small shared library that performs an x86 CPU feature guard
check that compares the features enabled during compile-time with the
features available at run-time (using the `CPUID` instruction). This
comparison is done during static initialization and the process is
aborted with an error message if we have compiled with a feature that is
not supported by the current CPU.

Such a check is already performed during static initialization of the
library `libtensorflow_framework.so.2`, but since this library performs
many actions during initialization, there is a high risk of triggering
an illegal instruction before we reach the check, depending on the
(undefined) static initialization order.

Because of this we compile a separate shared library that we load as a
self-check before loading `_pywrap_tensorflow_internal.so`.

We also change to use `<iostream>` for printing in case of a failed
check, as use of the logging framework might itself trigger an
illegal instruction (it did in my testing).

Tested by attempting to use a wheel built with AVX-512 on an AMD CPU:

Before:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
Illegal instruction
```

After:

```
$ python -c 'import tensorflow'
The TensorFlow library was compiled to use AVX512F instructions, but these aren't available on your machine.
Aborted
```","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/b88448050295233420ed8c4b6f23dda151c0de20"},{"sha":"e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635","author":{"name":"Hkon Sandsmark","email":"86bd98830e486454d7a971712b82439e4feff002@graphcore.ai"},"message":"Run buildifier","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/e3594cff84b705bf3af2312bf43fa3598244b635"},{"sha":"109d8fb0cd2972cb07fadc772ad9deaf24ae61da","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #48024 from hakos:cpu_feature_guard_lib
